00:44:34.740 --> 00:44:37.080
most of whom I've worked
with for more than a year--

00:44:37.080 --> 00:44:40.320
who didn't know this
about me at all.

00:44:40.320 --> 00:44:45.300
How do you be out when
it's not directly related

00:44:45.300 --> 00:44:46.302
to your profession?

00:44:46.302 --> 00:44:48.510
DEDEKER WINSTON: Well, I
want you to talk about this.

00:44:48.510 --> 00:44:51.060
But just to give a
little bit of a preamble,

00:44:51.060 --> 00:44:55.080
that's definitely a phenomenon
of what we call mononomativity,

00:44:55.080 --> 00:44:57.270
which is similar to
heteronormativity, which

00:44:57.270 --> 00:44:59.870
is the assumption that
everyone is heterosexual

00:44:59.870 --> 00:45:01.120
and not even questioning that.

00:45:01.120 --> 00:45:02.580
And it's kind of
the same thing is

00:45:02.580 --> 00:45:05.820
that we have this monomormative
assumption that everyone

00:45:05.820 --> 00:45:07.440
is seeking monogamy,
or everyone is

00:45:07.440 --> 00:45:09.427
in a monogamous relationship.

00:45:09.427 --> 00:45:11.760
So that's the hard thing, is
even if you're not actively

00:45:11.760 --> 00:45:14.425
trying to lie, or cover
things up, or be in a closet,

00:45:14.425 --> 00:45:16.050
that there's still
this assumption that

00:45:16.050 --> 00:45:18.260
often gets placed upon people.

00:45:18.260 --> 00:45:20.950
EMILY MATLACK: And may
blow past them, regardless.

00:45:20.950 --> 00:45:24.000
it But I want you to share
your experience at work.

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:26.910
JASE LINDGREN: Yeah, so I worked
for a visual effects company

00:45:26.910 --> 00:45:28.110
in Los Angeles.

00:45:28.110 --> 00:45:30.240
And there's a similar
thing, where I even

00:45:30.240 --> 00:45:34.470
have the podcast to be able
to talk about while I'm there.

00:45:34.470 --> 00:45:37.302
But there is that
interesting balance of I

00:45:37.302 --> 00:45:39.510
don't want to be just throwing
it in everyone's faces

00:45:39.510 --> 00:45:40.334
all the time.

00:45:40.334 --> 00:45:42.000
But at the same time,
yeah, I would like

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:43.710
to be creating more awareness.

00:45:43.710 --> 00:45:48.660
And as someone who is willing
to spend the energy on talking

00:45:48.660 --> 00:45:50.580
about this and
answering questions,

00:45:50.580 --> 00:45:53.130
I'd like to put myself
out there for that.

00:45:53.130 --> 00:45:57.030
And what I found
is it's more just--

00:45:57.030 --> 00:46:01.050
as a polyamorous person,
on just a day-to-day level,

00:46:01.050 --> 00:46:06.230
it can be really easy to get
into these habits of using

00:46:06.230 --> 00:46:10.310
vague language around your
relationships of like, well,

00:46:10.310 --> 00:46:13.640
maybe I'll just say girlfriend,
when really what I mean

00:46:13.640 --> 00:46:14.540
is partner.

00:46:14.540 --> 00:46:17.420
Or really what I mean
is this person I just

00:46:17.420 --> 00:46:19.665
started dating that you
haven't heard about before,

00:46:19.665 --> 00:46:22.040
but you've already heard me
call someone else girlfriend.

00:46:22.040 --> 00:46:23.060
And if I just say
girlfriend, you're

00:46:23.060 --> 00:46:25.520
not going to ask me questions,
and I can tell my story

00:46:25.520 --> 00:46:29.765
and not have to stop it to
answer all your questions.

00:46:29.765 --> 00:46:32.912
But it's essentially trying
to pick the moments when

00:46:32.912 --> 00:46:34.370
you do have the
time and the energy

00:46:34.370 --> 00:46:38.360
to have those conversations,
and to just work it

00:46:38.360 --> 00:46:42.470
into your story in the
same way that if I have

00:46:42.470 --> 00:46:46.800
a male partner, rather than
trying to avoid that fact,

00:46:46.800 --> 00:46:48.350
I would just say,
oh, my boyfriend.

00:46:48.350 --> 00:46:51.980
Or even just saying my partner
will make people go, what?

00:46:51.980 --> 00:46:53.692
What do you mean by partner?

00:46:53.692 --> 00:46:55.400
Because we have that
association with it.

00:46:55.400 --> 00:46:56.930
It's just like
finding little ways

00:46:56.930 --> 00:47:01.790
to put that in the conversation,
or something like, oh, I'm

00:47:01.790 --> 00:47:03.110
going on a first date tonight.

00:47:03.110 --> 00:47:04.310
I'm excited about it--

00:47:04.310 --> 00:47:05.090
when you're having
that like, what

00:47:05.090 --> 00:47:06.756
are you doing this
weekend conversation.

00:47:06.756 --> 00:47:09.080
It's finding those
little ways to be

00:47:09.080 --> 00:47:12.260
just a little more conscious
about that mononormative

00:47:12.260 --> 00:47:15.290
assumption that everyone's
going to be coming at it with,

00:47:15.290 --> 00:47:18.350
to just make that little
mention to make it clear what

00:47:18.350 --> 00:47:20.227
your relationships are like.

00:47:20.227 --> 00:47:21.560
That's something I found for me.

00:47:21.560 --> 00:47:22.299
